938    /**
939    * We only do forward type inference. We do not do full backwards
940    * type inference.
941    *
942    * In other words, if we have,
943    * <code>
944    * var x = f();
945    * g(x);
946    * </code>
947    * a forward type-inference engine would try to figure out the type
948    * of "x" from the return type of "f". A backwards type-inference engine
949    * would try to figure out the type of "x" from the parameter type of "g".
950    *
951    * However, there are a few special syntactic forms where we do some
952    * some half-assed backwards type-inference, because programmers
953    * expect it in this day and age. To take an example from Java,
954    * <code>
955    * List<String> x = Lists.newArrayList();
956    * </code>
957    * The Java compiler will be able to infer the generic type of the List
958    * returned by newArrayList().
959    *
960    * In much the same way, we do some special-case backwards inference for
961    * JS. Those cases are enumerated here.
962    */
